{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9cn91l/machine_epsilon_calculated_using_single_and/", "text": "Why does calculating machine epsilon using floats give a different result than calculating machine epsilon using doubles?", "score": 2, "comments": [{"body": "Because the machine epsilon is different for different precisions. It's the smallest relative difference between two adjacent numbers - if you have more precision, the machine epsilon is smaller, because (roughly) you have more bits to specify what number you're talking about.", "id": "e5bxzf8", "replies": []}], "title": "Machine epsilon calculated using single and double precision"}